had any symptoms that could be attributable to this stone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of the stone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and no further action","Repeat CT scan in 12 months","Percutaneous nephrolithotomy","Ureteroscopy and laser ablation","Extracorporeal lithotripsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stone appears to be an incidental finding. This patient does not have any evidence of urinary tract obstruction or infection, so a measured assessment can be made of what to do with this stone. If the stone had been small (\u0026lt;5 mm) it could have been kept under surveillance and imaging repeated in 12 months to see if there had been any change in size. However, there are certain indications where active treatment should be considered for asymptomatic renal calculi and these include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Estone \u0026gt;5mm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Estone growing in size\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esingle kidney\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eoccupational (need to be stone free e.g. pilot, military)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Erecurrent urinary tract infections\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the size of the stone suggests that some form of intervention is required. Of the options provided, \u003Cstrong\u003Eextracorporeal lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the least invasive and should be offered first.This approach is ideal for stones up to 10 mm, but is still the valid approach for 10 - 20 mm stones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most small, asymptomatic renal calculi can be kept under active surveillance."],"references":["Turk C, Petrik A, Sarica K, et al.  EAU Guidelines on Interventional Treatment for Urolithiasis. Euro Urol 2016; 69:475\u201382."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"345"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-17T15:09:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T09:46:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"dat